if i have to upload a backend project file in github what should be format and gitignore should containTo upload a backend project to GitHub, you should follow a clear directory structure and include a .gitignore file to keep your repository clean and secure.Recommended Project FormatThe standard way to organize a backend project is to separate your source code from configuration and documentation. Use a flat root directory with the following structure:Root Directory: Contains entry-level files like README.md, LICENSE, and environment config./src: Houses all your source code (e.g., controllers, models, routes)./tests: Contains your unit and integration tests./docs: Stores project-specific documentation or API references./config: Contains database settings and other app configurations.Entry Point: A file in the root or /src (like index.js, main.py, or app.java) that starts the server.What your .gitignore should containThe .gitignore file must be placed in the root of your project. It tells Git which files or folders to ignore, preventing you from uploading sensitive or unnecessary data.Common categories to include:Dependencies: Large folders like node_modules/ or venv/ that can be re-installed from package files.Secrets: Files like .env which contain API keys and passwords. Never upload these to GitHub.Build Artifacts: Compiled files or folders like dist/, build/, or target/.Logs: Runtime log files such as *.log or npm-debug.log.System Files: OS-specific metadata like .DS_Store (macOS) or Thumbs.db (Windows).Pro-Tips for SetupUse Templates: You can find pre-made, language-specific templates on the GitHub Gitignore Repository or use tools like gitignore.io to generate one.Automatic Generation: If using VS Code, you can use extensions like the Git Ignore extension by codezombie to add standard patterns automatically.Clean Existing Repo: If you accidentally committed a file that should be ignored, use git rm -r --cached <filename> to untrack it without deleting it from your local computer.23 sitesGitHub folder structure for embedded projects? - EEVblogWhen starting out, don't overthink the structure - it will naturally evolve as your project grows. A simple, readable starting poi...EEVblogFolder Structure for API's - Beginner, Intermediate, and ...A recommended starting point for a beginner's Node.js Express API project involves an `src` folder to contain most of the code. In...6mYouTube·PedroTechThe Folder Structure for Every Golang Project - GitHub GistGo - The Ultimate Folder Structure. ... Here's a brief explanation of the key directories: cmd/ : This directory contains applicat...GistShow allwhat should be exactly in gitignore fileThe exact content of your .gitignore file depends entirely on the programming language and framework you are using. Because it contains text, it must be named exactly .gitignore with no file extension (like .txt).Below are the exact templates for the most common backend languages. Copy and paste the one that matches your project into a file named .gitignore in your project's root folder.🟢 Node.js / Expresstext# Dependency directories
